SIMPLE: neighborhood
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Neighborhood
<hw>Neigh"bor*hood</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Written also
<ets>neighbourhood</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or
condition of being a neighbor; the state of being or dwelling near;
proximity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then the prison and the palace were in awful
<qex>neighborhood</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ld. Lytton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A place near; vicinity; adjoining district; a region
the inhabitants of which may be counted as neighbors; <as>as, he lives
in my <ex>neighborhood</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The inhabitants who live in the vicinity of each
other; <as>as, the fire alarmed all the
<ex>neighborhood</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The disposition becoming a neighbor; neighborly
kindness or good will.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Jer.
Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Vicinity; vicinage; proximity.</syn> <usage> --
<er>Neighborhood</er>, <er>Vicinity</er>. <xex>Neighborhood</xex> is
Anglo-Saxon, and <xex>vicinity</xex> is Latin. <xex>Vicinity</xex> does
not commonly denote so close a connection as <xex>neighborhood</xex>. A
<xex>neighborhood</xex> is a more immediately <xex>vicinity.</xex> The
houses immediately adjoining a square are in the <xex>neighborhood</xex>
of that square; those which are somewhat further removed are also in the
<xex>vicinity</xex> of the square.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neighboring</ent>⟦br⟧
